Lab Two: Exploring Image Data¶

Sian Xiao & Tingting Zhao¶

1. Business Understanding¶

1.1 Data Source¶

The Chinese MNIST (Chinese numbers handwritten characters images) dataset is downloaded from Kaggle. It's collected and modified from a project at Newcastle University.

In the original project, one hundred Chinese nationals took part in data collection. Each participant wrote with a standard black ink pen all 15 numbers in a table with 15 designated regions drawn on a white A4 paper. This process was repeated 10 times with each participant. Each sheet was scanned at the resolution of 300x300 pixels. It resulted a dataset of 15000 images, each representing one character from a set of 15 characters (grouped in samples, grouped in suites, with 10 samples/volunteer and 100 volunteers).

The modified dataset (Kaggle) contains the following:

  • an index file, chinese_mnist.csv
  • a folder with 15,000 jpg images, sized 64 x 64.

1.2 Data Significance¶

This is a optical character recognition (OCR) problem, and our task is to recognize the character each image has.

In China, the checks are required to be written in both numbers and Chinese characters. Since Chinese characters are hard to change to another, this reduces the chance of fraud. These 15 characters can cover almost all possible numbers in Chinese. For example, 2301 and be written as "二千零一“ or simply ”二三零一“, the former one is regularly used expression and the latter one is just map all digits to characters, but both of them can be identified by Chinese. The banks might be interested in the results since they can be used to validate checks. For the first expression of numbers, this should be combined with NLP to give valid numbers. Definitely, the prediction algorithm should predict every images to its true character.

1.3 Data Description¶

The .csv file contains a data frame with following attributes:

  • suite_id: There are totally 100 suites, each created by a volunteer.
  • sample_id: Each volunteer created 10 samples.
  • code: Each sample contains characters from 0 to 100M (totally 15 Chinese number characters). This is a code used to identify.
  • value: Numerical value of each character.
  • character:The actual Chinese character corresponding to one number.

The mapping of value, character and code is shown below:

# cite from https://stackoverflow.com/questions/51205502/convert-a-black-and-white-image-to-array-of-numbers
def read_image(name):
    path = 'data/image/' + name
    img = cv2.imread(path, 0)
    img_re = cv2.bitwise_not(img)
    img_new = img_re/255.0
    return img_new


path_example = 'input_1_1_1.jpg'

# Here I modified the plot_gallery function to choose images randomly.
# The data frame is collected by code, so the first 100 rows are all the same characters.

def plot_gallery(images, labels, h, w, n_row=5, n_col=6, random_=False):
    """Helper function to plot a gallery of portraits"""
    plt.figure(figsize=(1.6 * n_col, 1.6 * n_row))
    plt.subplots_adjust(bottom=0, left=.01, right=.99, top=.90, hspace=.35)
    for i in range(n_row * n_col):
        plt.subplot(n_row, n_col, i + 1)
        index = random.randrange(0, len(images)) if random_ else i
        plt.imshow(images[index].reshape((h, w)), cmap=plt.cm.gray)
        plt.title(labels[index], size=12)
        plt.xticks(())
        plt.yticks(())


plot_gallery(X, y, h, w, random_=True)

def reconstruct_image(trans_obj, org_features):
    low_rep = trans_obj.transform(org_features)
    rec_image = trans_obj.inverse_transform(low_rep)
    return low_rep, rec_image

from sklearn.neighbors import KNeighborsClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split


def acc(X_pca_features, X_rpca_features, y):
    knn_pca = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=1)
    knn_rpca = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=1)
    pca_train, pca_test, rpca_train, rpca_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        X_pca_features, X_rpca_features, y, test_size=0.2, train_size=0.8)
    knn_pca.fit(pca_train, y_train)
    acc_pca = accuracy_score(knn_pca.predict(pca_test), y_test)
    knn_rpca.fit(rpca_train, y_train)
    acc_rpca = accuracy_score(knn_rpca.predict(rpca_test), y_test)
    return 100*acc_pca, 100*acc_rpca


pca, rpca = [], []
for i in range(10):
    acc_pca, acc_rpca = acc(X_pca_features, X_rpca_features, y)
    pca.append(acc_pca)
    rpca.append(acc_rpca)

pca_mean, pca_std = round(np.mean(pca), 2), round(np.std(pca), 2)
rpca_mean, rpca_std = round(np.mean(rpca), 2), round(np.std(rpca), 2)

print(f"PCA feature accuracy:{pca_mean}, PCA feature std: {pca_std}")
print(
    f"random PCA feature accuracy: {rpca_mean}, random PCA feature std: {rpca_std}")

PCA feature accuracy:54.37, PCA feature std: 0.77
random PCA feature accuracy: 54.47, random PCA feature std: 0.81
N component PCA rPCA
wall time Cum_var Accuracy wall time Cum_var Accuracy
2000 15.5 s 0.9998 \ 14.3 s 0.9998 \
750 6.04 s 0.9513 54.37(0.77) 5.85 s 0.9513 54.47(0.81)

According to the cumulative explained variation and KNeighborsClassifier model accuracy, PCA and random PCA are of same ability at representing the images with fewer components. However, random PCA is faster when the component is larger(2000). So random PCA is preferred because it maintains the same accuracy at the same time is faster to compute.

def apply_daisy(row, shape):
    feat = daisy(row.reshape(shape), step=20, radius=20,
                 rings=2, histograms=8, orientations=8,
                 visualize=False)
    return feat.reshape((-1))

def acc(X_pca_features, daisy_features, y):
    knn_pca = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=1)
    knn_dsy = KNeighborsClassifier(n_neighbors=1)

    pca_train, pca_test, dsy_train, dsy_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(
        X_pca_features, daisy_features, y, test_size=0.2, train_size=0.8)

    knn_pca.fit(pca_train, y_train)
    acc_pca = accuracy_score(knn_pca.predict(pca_test), y_test)

    knn_dsy.fit(dsy_train, y_train)
    acc_dsy = accuracy_score(knn_dsy.predict(dsy_test), y_test)

    return 100*acc_pca, 100*acc_dsy


pca, dsy = [], []
for i in range(10):
    acc_pca, acc_dsy = acc(X_pca_features, daisy_features, y)
    pca.append(acc_pca)
    dsy.append(acc_dsy)

pca_mean, pca_std = round(np.mean(pca), 2), round(np.std(pca), 2)
dsy_mean, dsy_std = round(np.mean(dsy), 2), round(np.std(dsy), 2)

print(f"PCA feature accuracy: {pca_mean}, PCA feature accuracy std: {pca_std}")
print(
    f"DAISY feature accuracy: {dsy_mean}, DAISY feature accuracy std: {dsy_std}")

PCA feature accuracy: 54.24, PCA feature accuracy std: 0.95
DAISY feature accuracy: 87.15, DAISY feature accuracy std: 0.47

             for l in lines if "top3" in l and "succedd" in l]
top1_accuracies = np.zeros((4, 4))
top3_accuracies = np.zeros((4, 4))
for i in range(16):
    top1_accuracies[i//4, i % 4] = top1_accu[i]
    top3_accuracies[i//4, i % 4] = (np.array(top1_accu) +
                                    np.array(top2_accu)+np.array(top3_accu))[i]

Considering calculation time, we did the DAISY parameter search on M2, here we only show the grid search results and demonstrate using the best parameter in following block. The files test.py and test.txt can be found here.

The heatmap on the left shows the accuracy of top1 hits, the one on the right shows the accuracy of top3 hits. As the plot shows: For Chinese MNIST data set, when steps or radius parameters are larger the accuracies are lower. However, when step or radius are small(=5 for example), the change of radius to accuracy is less sensitive than the change of step to accuracy.

Which is quite intuitive: When step is large, there is space in the image left uncaptured, so the accuracy is low; when radius is big, because the size differences of written Chinese character, key point in one image capture the whole character, key point in another image may only capture part of the character, which will also end up with low accuracy. In this case, tune the ring number parameter may get better accuracy.

One point need to be mentioned, there is a lot of empty space in the figure (all white, or all black in the original images), pre-process the image more may also enhance the accuracy: for example, get rid off all the white spaces and center the characters.

4.2 Key point matching method¶

In [29]:
from multiprocessing import Pool
from skimage.feature import match_descriptors, daisy


def train_test_split(X, y):
    # split training and testing set randomly. won't have bais because every person write 10 times
    X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = [], [], [], []
    for code in range(15):
        index = list(range(1000))
        random.seed(7324)
        random.shuffle(index)
        for i in index[:500]:
            X_train.append(X[code*1000+i])
            y_train.append(y[code*1000+i])
        for i in index[500:]:
            X_test.append(X[code*1000+i])
            y_test.append(y[code*1000+i])
    return X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test


def extract_descriptors(imgSet, step, radius, rings):
    # extract DAISY feature
    desSet = []
    for img_1d in imgSet:
        img_2d = img_1d.reshape(64, 64)
        fea = daisy(img_2d, step=step, radius=radius, rings=rings,
                    histograms=8, orientations=8, visualize=False)
        des = fea.reshape(fea.shape[0]*fea.shape[1], -1)
        desSet.append(des)
    return desSet


def massive_matching_DAISY(des_img):
    # kep point match
    match_numbers = []
    for i, des in enumerate(X_train):
        matches = match_descriptors(
            des_img, des, cross_check=True,  metric=None, p=2, max_distance=np.inf, max_ratio=1.0)
        match_numbers.append((matches.shape[0], i))

    match_numbers.sort(key=lambda x: -x[0])  # sort as most matching points
    return y_train[match_numbers[0][1]], y_train[match_numbers[1][1]], y_train[match_numbers[2][1]]


# split training and testing set
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y)
X_train = extract_descriptors(X_train, 5, 10, 2)
X_test = extract_descriptors(X_test, 5, 10, 2)


# parallel running key point match
with Pool(36) as p:
    results = p.map(massive_matching_DAISY, [i for i in X_test])


# hit count
top1, top2, top3 = [0]*15, [0]*15, [0]*15
for i, des in enumerate(X_test):
    one, two, three = results[i]
    if one == y_test[i]:
        top1[y_test[i]-1] += 1
    elif two == y_test[i]:
        top2[y_test[i]-1] += 1
    elif three == y_test[i]:
        top3[y_test[i]-1] += 1

fail = [500-top1[i]-top2[i]-top3[i] for i in range(15)]

From the results we can see, code 1 (character "零"), code 2 (character "一"), code 5 (character "四"), code 9 (character "八"), code 11(character "十") can be accurately predicted (more than 90%), probably because they are very distinguishable from other characters(character "零", "四"), or because they are kind of eigen characters (character "一", "八", "十"). Though the correlation matrices from 3.5 shows the DAISY feature can easily capture the difference between the eighen characters(character "一", "八") from others, we are using key point matching which doesn't focus on the whole feature space, so the method may struggle at distinguishing the characters containing these eigen characters from the eigen characters.

code 3 (character "二") has the lowest accuracy(around 72%), which is hard to distinguish from code 2 (character "一") and code 3 (character "三"). Similar to code 8 (character "七"), which may be hard to be distinguished from code 10 (character "九") or code 14 (character "万").
